2025/12/15 00:30:37 INFO dspy.teleprompt.gepa.gepa: Iteration 1: Proposed new text for generate_answer.predict: ## Task Instruction
Predict the Iris Species based on Petal and Sepal Dimensions

## Task Description
This task aims to predict the species of an iris flower given its petal and sepal dimensions in centimeters. The task involves classification of the flower into one of three species: Setosa, Virginica, or Versicolor.

## Input Format
The input will consist of the following dimensions:
- Petal length in centimeters
- Petal width in centimeters
- Sepal length in centimeters
- Sepal width in centimeters

## Assumptions and Limitations
The task can be performed using a classification algorithm, and the input dimensions will be used as features to predict the species of the iris flower. The task assumes that the input dimensions are within the valid range for each sepal and petal dimension.

## Known Characteristics of Iris Species
- Setosa iris flowers have small petals (less than 1 cm) and narrow petal width (less than 0.5 cm), with sepal length between 5-7 cm and sepal width between 2-4 cm.
- Virginica iris flowers have larger petals (more than 1 cm) and narrower petal width (less than 1 cm), with sepal length between 7-10 cm and sepal width between 3-5 cm.
- Versicolor iris flowers have medium-sized petals (between 1-4 cm) and moderate widths (between 0.2-1.3 cm), with sepal length between 5-7 cm and sepal width between 2-4 cm.

## Classification Strategy
The task can be performed using a classification algorithm such as a decision tree or a logistic regression model. The algorithm will analyze the input petal and sepal dimensions to predict the species of the iris flower.

## Feedback and Evaluation Metrics
The performance of the task will be evaluated using a feedback score, which will indicate whether the predicted species is correct or not. A feedback score of 1 indicates a correct prediction, while a score of 0 indicates an incorrect prediction.

## Task Output
The task output will be a predicted species of the iris flower (Setosa, Virginica, or Versicolor) along with a reasoning explanation for the prediction.
